{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:52:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:52:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16132"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16132"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.05,0.45,0.05,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8823"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60106"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5298"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy involves distinct immunological changes to support foetal development and maintain maternal health. These changes occur in stages, with each trimester having unique immunological characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best characterises the immunological state during the second trimester of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pro-inflammatory","T helper 1 immune state","Anti-inflammatory","Increased cytotoxic T cell activity","Heightened immune surveillance"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the second trimester of pregnancy, the maternal immune system shifts to an \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-inflammatory\u003C/strong\u003E state. This is crucial for supporting foetal growth and development while preventing maternal immune rejection of the foetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPro-inflammatory\u003C/strong\u003E - The first trimester is more pro-inflammatory to facilitate implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET helper 1 immune state\u003C/strong\u003E - The second trimester is characterised by a T helper 2 dominant state\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased cytotoxic T cell activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Cytotoxic activity is reduced to prevent foetal rejection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeightened immune surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E - Immune surveillance is modulated to tolerate the foetus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anti-inflammatory state is essential for maintaining a healthy pregnancy and ensuring the foetus is not attacked by the maternal immune system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The second trimester of pregnancy is characterised by an anti-inflammatory immune state.","During the second trimester, the maternal immune system shifts to support foetal growth and development."],"references":["Mor G, Cardenas I, Abrahams V, Guller S. Inflammation and pregnancy: the role of the immune system at the implantation site. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2011 Mar;1221(1):80-7. doi: 10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05938.x. PMID: 21401634; PMCID: PMC3078586.","Mor G, Cardenas I. The immune system in pregnancy: a unique complexity. Am J Reprod Immunol. 2010 Jun;63(6):425-33. doi: 10.1111/j.1600-0897.2010.00836.x. Epub 2010 Mar 29. PMID: 20367629; PMCID: PMC3025805.","Abu-Raya B, Michalski C, Sadarangani M, Lavoie PM. Maternal Immunological Adaptation During Normal Pregnancy. Front Immunol. 2020 Oct 7;11:575197. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2020.575197. PMID: 33133091; PMCID: PMC7579415.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16132"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T21:14:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T21:57:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8823"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74612"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving inform